subCards.title: Italy Deals Air-Defense Blow to NATO Ally's Pro-Putin Leader
subCards.abstract: Rome's decision to relocate one of its SAMP/T anti-air missile systems has left a NATO ally with a gap in its defences.

images.title: SAMP/T Mamba AA system in Slovakia 2023
images.caption: A French-Italian SAMP/T Mamba air defence system is seen at Kuchyna air base, north of Bratislava, Slovakia on April 19, 2023. Rome is now withdrawing the system after a year-long deployment.

$values.text:
Possible response:

**Italian withdrawal of air-defense system angers Slovakian PM**

- Italy decided to remove the SAMP/T platform from Slovakia, which was deployed there after Slovakia donated its S-300 system to Ukraine.
- Slovakian PM Robert Fico accused President Zuzana Čaputová of "servility to foreign interests" and said the withdrawal would leave Slovakia vulnerable to attacks.
- Slovakia is facing a gap in its air defense and military aviation, and is in talks with the U.S. to acquire a Patriot system.

**Slovakian PM opposes Western strategy on Ukraine**

- Fico returned to power in September 2023 with a pro-Russian stance and an opposition to arming Ukraine.
- He ended Slovakia's active military support for Kyiv and called for an immediate ceasefire that would favor Moscow.
- He also criticized former British PM Boris Johnson for allegedly discouraging peace talks in 2022.

subCards.title: Giada De Laurentiis makes Scottsdale debut. What to expect at her new Italian restaurants
subCards.abstract: Food Network chef Giada De Laurentiis opens two new restaurants inside the Caesars Republic Scottsdale hotel. What to expect at Luna and Pronto.

images.title: Giada De Laurentiis
images.caption: Giada De Laurentiis

$values.text:
**New restaurants from Giada De Laurentiis:** The celebrity chef opens two Italian eateries at the Caesars Republic Scottsdale hotel on March 6. Luna by Giada is a sophisticated dining room with family photos and art, while Pronto by Giada is a casual cafe with gelati and paninis.

**Luna by Giada menu:** The restaurant features some of De Laurentiis' signature dishes, such as lemon spaghetti and chicken panzanella, as well as new items, such as lemon pizza and Nodi Marini alla vodka. The menu also includes lobster bucatini, pork chop saltimbocca and Bistecca alla Fiorentina.

**Pronto by Giada menu:** The cafe offers breakfast and lunch options, such as sausage and egg sandwich, smoked salmon bagel, caprese panini and turkey, bacon and avocado panini. Pronto also serves gelati imported from Los Angeles.

subCards.title: The Houthis Are Very, Very Pleased
subCards.abstract: Since staking claim to the Palestinian cause, the Yemeni militants have come to seem unstoppable.

images.title: Have the Houthis Become Unstoppable?

$values.text:
The article explores the rise and influence of ***Abdulmalik al-Houthi***, the leader of the **Houthis**, a militant movement in northern Yemen. It:

- Provides historical and biographical details about the Houthis' origins, ideology, and conflicts with the Yemeni state and Saudi Arabia.
- Explains the Houthis' bold and provocative actions in **defending Gaza** and **attacking commercial ships** in the Red Sea, which have gained them global attention and support.
- Interviews **Abdelmalek al-Ejri**, a Houthi diplomat in Oman, who reveals the Houthis' **confidence, vision, and ambition** to be the main political and military actor in Yemen and the region, surpassing even Iran.
- Highlights the **mystery and hostility** that surround the Houthis, who have no clear political agenda, no birth certificate, and no foreign contact.
- Emphasizes the role of **Saudi Arabia** in creating and supporting the Houthis, and the consequences of their growing power and aggression for the region and the world.

images.title: A Colorado ski town can't fill a job with a $167,000 salary because potential candidates can't afford to live there

$values.text:
**Housing crisis in Steamboat Springs, Colorado**

- Even high earners such as city employees and doctors are being priced out of the town due to skyrocketing housing costs.
- The housing market is driven by the rise of remote work and the short-term rental market, which attract guests from cities and reduce the supply of homes for locals.
- The town is facing a major housing battle, with disagreements over how to address the issues.

subCards.title: Putin Ally Says Neighboring Country Will Not Exist in Five Years
subCards.abstract: Margarita Simonyan said the Armenian prime minister's criticism of Moscow is leading his nation to complete destruction.

images.title: Editor-in chief of RT Margarita Simonyan
images.caption: Editor-in chief of RT Margarita Simonyan speaks during a meeting of Vladimir Putin's supporters ahead of 2024 Presidential Elections, on January 31, 2024 in Moscow, Russia.

$values.text: The article reports on ***Margarita Simonyan***, the editor-in-chief of the Kremlin mouthpiece **RT**, and her harsh criticism of **Armenian Prime Minister Nikol Pashinyan**. She called him a **"traitor"** to the Armenian people and said that **"there will be no Armenia in five years"** if he remains in power. She blamed him for Armenia's suspension from the **Collective Security Treaty Organization (CSTO)**, a Moscow-led security bloc, and said that **"Armenia will not exist at all"** if voters continue to support him. She made her remarks at the **World Youth Festival** in Russia's Krasnodar region, where she received applause from the audience. The article also provides context and background on the ongoing conflict between **Armenia and Azerbaijan** over the **Nagorno-Karabakh region**, a breakaway territory recognized internationally as part of Azerbaijan but populated by ethnic Armenians. It explains how Armenia's participation in the CSTO has been an issue for years, especially after Azerbaijan launched an offensive in the region last September, followed by the exodus of most of the Armenian population. It also highlights the political and military implications of Armenia stepping away from the CSTO, which is seen as Russia's equivalent to NATO.

subCards.title: 'Working my tail-end off just to get by’: This Walmart worker blasted older Americans for calling young folks lazy — blamed them for 'creating' the inflation crisis, ruining the economy
subCards.abstract: The video has struck a chord.

images.title: Walmart employee fires back at claim Gen Z is lazy
images.caption: Walmart employee fires back at claim Gen Z is lazy

$values.text: The article explores the economic challenges faced by ***Gen Z***, especially those working full-time jobs at **Walmart**, and how they are often blamed for the current state of the economy. It cites a viral video by **TikTok user @chailynt**, who works at Walmart and expresses her frustration with the media's portrayal of Gen Z as lazy and unwilling to work 9-5 jobs. She shares her personal experience of working **40 hours a week** and still struggling to afford basic living expenses, and challenges the older generations for letting the economy "run to hell" and placing the burden on Gen Z. She argues that Gen Z did not cause the inflation crisis, but rather is trying to fix the mistakes of previous generations. The article provides data from the **U.S. Census Bureau** to show how the housing market, wages, and other essentials have changed significantly over the past 20 years, making it harder for young adults to afford basic needs and achieve financial stability.

subCards.title: After being shot down by a judge, Kari Lake withdraws appeal on ballot return envelopes
subCards.abstract: Kari Lake had dropped her notice to review the envelopes that more than 1 million Maricopa County voters used to return their ballots in 2022.

images.title: Kari Lake speaks during a television interview before Republican presidential candidate former President Donald Trump arrives at a primary election night party in Nashua, New Hampshire, on Jan. 23, 2024.
images.caption: Kari Lake speaks during a television interview before Republican presidential candidate former President Donald Trump arrives at a primary election night party in Nashua, New Hampshire, on Jan. 23, 2024.

$values.text: The article reports on ***Kari Lake's*** decision to **withdraw her notice of appeal** on the *ballot return envelopes* that were used by more than *1 million Maricopa County voters* in the 2022 governor's race. Lake, a *Republican Senate candidate*, had sought to review the envelopes under the **Arizona Public Records Law**, claiming they contained voter signatures that could reveal fraud. However, a **Maricopa County Superior Court judge** had **denied her request** and affirmed the county recorder's decision to keep the envelopes confidential under a specific exemption for signatures. Lake's withdrawal ends one of her court cases related to her **17,000-vote loss** to Democrat *Gov. Katie Hobbs*. Lake had previously labeled the 2022 elections as *"rigged"* and *"stolen"*, and vowed to take her case to the **U.S. Supreme Court**. The county recorder, *Stephen Richer*, praised the court's decision and urged voters to **turn in their early ballots** before the March 19 presidential preference election.
